Durban - Police have opened a case of reckless and negligent driving after a group of cyclists were knocked on Sunday morning. According to KZN police spokesperson Lieutenant Colonel Thulani Zwane, the group of cyclists had been travelling on the M4 Ruth First Highway in the north-bound lane when one of the cyclists were knocked by an unknown vehicle. Zwane said when the cyclist fell it caused other cyclists to collide with each other. He said the motorist failed to stop at the scene of the accident. Zwane said the cyclists opened a case at the Durban North SAPS. All cyclists were treated on scene and taken to the hospital according to Netcare 911's Shawn Herbst. In May Omesh Ramnarain was sentenced to 10 years in jail for knocking dead cyclists Jarred Dwyer and Richard da Silva on February 7, 2016. The duo had been cycling on the M4. Ramnarain was found guilty on two counts of culpable homicide. He is out on R30 000 pending his appeal next year. Daily News